# 2) Tiny robustness & coverage polish (no behavior change)

These are safe, parity-neutral additions — they just harden tests.

### A. Literal “#” at start

`.gitignore` treats `#` as a comment unless escaped. Add:

```go
{
  Group: "literals",
  Description: `\#file is a literal pattern for "#file"`,
  Patterns: []string{`\\#file`},
  Path: "#file", IsDir: false, ShouldIgnore: true,
}
```

Backed by the spec’s “line starting with `#` serves as a comment. Put a backslash in front of the first hash for patterns that begin with a hash.” ([Git][1])

### B. Sanity check: `foo/*` one-level rule

You already cover this, but it’s a good “lock”:

```go
{
  Group: "one-level",
  Description: "foo/* does not match foo/bar/hello.c",
  Patterns: []string{"foo/*"},
  Path: "foo/bar/hello.c", IsDir: false, ShouldIgnore: false,
}
```

Directly mirrors the manual example. ([Git][1])

